      "id": "1827626365757365",
      "title": "Slay the Spire 2 is stamping out infinites, and you're not prepared for what we've lost",
      "link": "https://steamstore-a.akamaihd.net/news/externalpost/PCGamesN/1827626365757365",
      "pubDate": "Fri, 20 Mar 2026 11:40:56 GMT",
      "publishedAt": "2026-03-20T11:40:56.000Z",
      "kind": "news",
      "category": "news",
      "sourceLabel": "PCGamesN",
      "author": "editor@pcgamesn.com",
      "official": false,
      "external": true,
      "image": "https://www.pcgamesn.com/wp-content/sites/pcgamesn/2026/03/slay-the-spire-2-patch-notes-beta-infinites-nerfed-balance-changes-all-classes-mega-crit-roguelike-deckbuilder-sts2-update-900x506.jpg",
      "summary": "Wave goodbye to many of your infinite combos as the first Slay the Spire 2 balance patch comes crashing down on our heads. Mega Crit has been studying our play carefully, and with the roguelike deckbuilder still surpassing half-a-million player peaks every day, it's had plenty of data to choose from. The aim of today's patch is making infinites harder to achieve - they won't be gone altogether, as they're a fundamental part of the StS 2 power curve, but they shouldn't be nearly as easy to get rolling. This Slay the Spire 2 update also introduces 'Phobia Mode,' designed to cut back on some of its more unsettling card designs.\nRead the rest of the story...\nRELATED LINKS:\nLost in Random: The Eternal Die proves roguelikes don't need to fill 100 hours\nHozy is a cozy decorating game that makes me want to rip up my carpet, and take a trip to Ikea\nAfter accidentally clobbering my friends in grimdark action-RPG No Rest for the Wicked, now I can do it on purpose",
      "summaryKo": "Wave goodbye to many of your infinite combos as the first Slay the Spire 2 balance patch comes crashing down on our heads. Mega Crit has been studying our play carefully, and with the roguelike deckbuilder still surpassing half-a-million player peaks every day, it's had plenty of data to choose from. The aim of today's patch is making infinites harder to achieve - they won't be gone altogether, as they're a fundamental part of the StS 2 power curve, but they shouldn't be nearly as easy to get rolling. This Slay the Spire 2 update also introduces 'Phobia Mode,' designed to cut back on some of its more unsettling card designs.",
      "body": "Wave goodbye to many of your infinite combos as the first Slay the Spire 2 balance patch comes crashing down on our heads. Mega Crit has been studying our play carefully, and with the roguelike deckbuilder still surpassing half-a-million player peaks every day, it's had plenty of data to choose from. The aim of today's patch is making infinites harder to achieve - they won't be gone altogether, as they're a fundamental part of the StS 2 power curve, but they shouldn't be nearly as easy to get rolling. This Slay the Spire 2 update also introduces 'Phobia Mode,' designed to cut back on some of its more unsettling card designs.\nRead the rest of the story...\nRELATED LINKS:\nLost in Random: The Eternal Die proves roguelikes don't need to fill 100 hours\nHozy is a cozy decorating game that makes me want to rip up my carpet, and take a trip to Ikea\nAfter accidentally clobbering my friends in grimdark action-RPG No Rest for the Wicked, now I can do it on purpose"
